 Local equities rebounded on resumed bargain hunting activities, as overall performance measures, NSE All Share Index (ASI) grew by .3.68 per cent, halting two days losing streak. The Nigerian stock market had tumbled for the second day, as investors retreated following profit takings and low market sentiments on high net worth stocks. The bullish activities was driven by consumer goods and oil and gas services stocks, which were highly sought after.
At the close of business, 30 stocks appreciated while six other stocks declined. Consequently, the All-Share Index gained 1.112.71 basis points or 3.68 per cent to close at 31,307.00 basis points as against 30,194.71 recorded the previous day, while the market capitalisation of equities appreciated by N490 billion to close at N13.789 trillion from N13.299 trillion.
Meanwhile, a turnover of 344.3 million shares exchanged in 4,457 deals was recorded in the day’s trading. Premium sub-sector was the most active (measured by turnover volume) with 173 million shares exchanged by investors in 2,057 deals.
Volume in the sub-sector was largely driven by activities in the shares of Zenith Bank Plc and FBNH Plc. Banking sub-sector boosted by activities in the shares of GTB Plc and Fidelity Bank Plc followed with a turnover of 94.2 million shares in 625 deals.
Further analysis of the day’s trading showed that ETI Plc topped the day’s gainers’ table with 10.00 per cent to close at N12.10 per share while UBA Plc followed with 9.65 per cent to close at N6.25 per share. Courtville Business Solution Nigeria Plc added 9.52 per cent to close at 23 kobo per share.
On the flip side, Eterna Oil Nigeria Plc led the losers’ with a drop of 8.75 per cent to close at N3.65 per share, while PZ Cussons Plc shed 4.71per cent to close at N8.10 per share. Nacho Plc plunged by 3.64 per cent to close at N3.18 per share.